        "scenario": "Onfido returns unexpected/malformed responses",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "Verify defensive deserialization. Ensure any non-2xx or malformed response is treated as a transient failure, not a permanent KYC rejection. A user should not be permanently blocked because Onfido returned a 500 that was misinterpreted."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "Thundering herd after Onfido recovery",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "NICE-TO-HAVE: If a circuit breaker is added, use half-open state with gradual ramp-up. If a retry queue is added, use jittered backoff to avoid slamming Onfido the moment it recovers."
      }
    ],
    "retry_config": "No retry logic mentioned. A single transient Onfido failure (network blip, 502) immediately fails the user's registration. At minimum, add 1 retry with a short delay (e.g., 500ms) before returning a 503.",
    "timeout_config": "5s timeout is reasonable given Onfido's 3s p99. However, without a circuit breaker, this 5s timeout becomes the tail latency for every request during an outage, which will exhaust connection pools under load.",
    "circuit_breakers": "None. This is the single biggest operational risk. During Onfido degradation, every inbound request will block for up to 5s, consuming server threads. At moderate traffic, the service will become completely unresponsive within minutes — a cascading failure that takes out more than just KYC.",
    "graceful_degradation": "None. The system has exactly two states: fully operational or fully broken. There is no intermediate state where users can register with deferred verification, no queuing mechanism, and no fast-fail path."
  },

